definition.value: The alpha-anomer of the pyranose form of D-paratose.
An sn-glycerol 3-phosphate having unspecified acyl groups at the 1- and 2-positions.
A chemical substance is a portion of matter of constant composition, composed of molecular entities of the same type or of different types.
The conjugate base of a 1-acyl-2-linoleoyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine compound formed by deprotonation of the phosphate OH group.
A mixture is a chemical substance composed of multiple molecules, at least two of which are of a different kind.
The conjugate base of 3-amino-4-hydroxybenzoic acid; major species at pH 7.3.

A polypeptide comprising N-decanoyltryptophan, asparagine, aspartic acid, threonine, glycine, ornithine, aspartic acid, D-alanine, aspartic acid, glycine, D-serine, threo-3-methylglutamic acid and 3-anthraniloylalanine (also known as kynurinine) coupled in sequence and lactonised by condensation of the carboxylic acid group of the 3-anthraniloylalanine  with the alcohol group of the threonine residue.
A polymer is a mixture, which is composed of macromolecules of different kinds and which may be differentiated by composition, length, degree of branching etc..
A homopolymer is a polymer composed of macromolecules, all of which are derived from one species of monomer.

A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of alpha-N-acetylneuraminyl-(2->6)-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosamine arising from deprotonation of the carboxylic acid function of the alpha-N-acetylneuraminyl residue.
A sialic acid anion arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group of an N-acylneuraminic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
The 6-O-sinapoyl derivative of D-glucono-1,5-lactone.

A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of alpha-N-acetylneuraminyl-(2->6)-beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-glucosylceramide arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group on the N-acetylneuraminyl residue; major species at pH 7.3.
A salt comprising separate ammonium cations and octahedral [PdCl6](2-) anions.
A salt comprising separate ammonium cations and octahedral [RhCl6](3-) anions.
A salt comprising separate ammonium cations and octahedral [IrCl6](2-) anions.
A salt comprising separate ammonium cations and octahedral [RuCl6](2-) anions.
A salt comprising separate ammonium cations and octahedral [RhCl6](3-) anions.
A salt comprising separate ammonium cations and square planar [PtCl4](2-) anions.
A salt comprising separate ammonium cations and square planar [PdCl4](2-) anions.
A disaccharide derivative comprising methyl alpha-D-galactoside having an alpha-D-galactosyl residue at the 3-position.
An ionic polymer is a polymer, composed of ionic macromolecules.
A deoxyribonucleoside containing a purine base.
A chlorophyll of photosynthetic bacteria, for example green sulfur bacteria.

A linear-fused organic heterotetracyclic compound consisting of a [1,3,2]dioxaphosphinane fused to a pyran ring which is in turn fused to a pteridine ring system. Molybdenum cofactor biosynthesis intermediate. Dehydrated derivative known as precursor Z.
A metal cation with a valence of two.
An atom or small molecule with a positive charge that does not contain carbon in covalent linkage, with a valency of one.
A silver atom having a net electric charge.
A lead atom having a net electric charge.
A selenium atom having a net electric charge.
A lead atom having a positive net electric charge.

The hexahydrate form of trisodium phosphonoformate. It is used as an antiviral agent in the treatment of cytomegalovirus retinitis (CMV retinitis, an inflamation of the retina that can lead to blindness) and as an alternative to ganciclovir for AIDS patients who require concurrent antiretroviral therapy but are unable to tolerate ganciclovir due to haematological toxicity.
A caesium atom having a net electric charge.
An aluminium atom having a net electric charge.
Benzaldehyde substituted at the 4-position by an N,N-dimethylamino group and at C-3 by bromine.
An N-acetyl-alpha-D-galactosaminide having a 4-nitrophenyl substituent at the anomeric position.
The pyranose form of D-galactosamine.
The open-chain form of D-galactosamine.
An N-acetyl-beta-D-galactosaminide having a methyl substituent at the anomeric position.
Any N-oxide of a purine or purine derivative.
An adenosine 5'-monophosphate having a salicyl group at the 3'-position; intermediate in mycobactin biosynthesis.
A generic term for all the possible tungsten cations (W6+, W4+, etc...)
A phosphatidic acid in which the phosphatidyl acyl groups are both oleoyl.
A compound resulting from partial hydrolysis of a phosphatidylcholine which removes one of the fatty acid groups.
A homopolymer, composed of gamma-poly(glutamic acid) macromolecule.
A gamma-poly(glutamic acid) polymer, composed of gamma-poly(L-glutamic acid) macromolecules.
The conjugate base of benzylpenicillenic acid.

A glycosylglucose where the glycosyl component is D-glycero-alpha-D-manno-heptopyranose attached via an alpha-(1->6)-linkage; the epitope of the lipooligosaccharide isolated from Haemophilus ducreyi strain ITM 2665.
